Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Tunisia. The Tunisian authorities have introduced measures to limit the spread of the virus.
Borders and travel
Commercial flights between Tunisia and all other countries were suspended at 11.59pm on 17 March. All maritime borders are closed. If you are already in Tunisia, and it is not essential that you remain, you should urgently contact your airline or tour operator and arrange to leave as soon as possible.
The British Embassy Tunis is issuing regular updates on Twitter and Facebook with the latest available information on flight departure options for British nationals wishing to leave Tunisia.
Local measures
A countrywide curfew came into effect on 18 March from 6pm to 6am. All schools and nurseries are closed, and caf√©s and restaurants are closing daily at 4pm. All sporting fixtures, conferences, public prayers and events have been cancelled.
Further information
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
You can find more information about cases in Tunisia on the TravelHealthPro country page.
